<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-755-920  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 755 920.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  Sept 11 1989 v3 n37 p50(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Private report, OPM study both fault Fed pay policy. (Office ofPersonnel Management)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Levine, Arnold S.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>An internal review by the Office of Personnel Management (OPM) andprivate report by the Wyatt Co find fault with federal pay policyand advocate retiring the General Schedule (GS) employee system.andO;Information on 55 percent of the federal white-collar work forcewas analyzed using OPM and Bureau of Labor Statistics data bases.andO;The analysis indicated that the government needs to recognizegeographic and occupational pay differences and adjust federalsalaries to reflect market rates.andP;  Cost of replacing the GS systemhas been estimated at $6 billion.andP;  The Wyatt study'srecommendation of locality-based pay was supported by federallabor unions.andP;  Suggested models for federal pay policy featurespecial pay rates for staffing problems, recruitment and retentionbonuses, and comprehensive salary surveys.andP;  OPM has nominated atask force to follow up on these reports.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Wyatt Co. (reports).andO;Topic:     United States. Office of Personnel ManagementSalaryGovernment AgencyEmployee BenefitsGovernment Regulation.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>